    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Give Back the Gold</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Errol Arne letter criticizes International Olympic Committee for taking gold medal away from Romanian gymnast Andreea Raducan because she tested positive for banned substance found in cold medicine</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Sports Editor:</p>
        <p>Rules are created so mayhem doesn't occur. There comes a time when a governing body has to take a step back and try to think outside the box. The International Olympic Committee needs to do this after stripping Andreea Raducan, the Romanian gymnast, of her gold medal in the all-around because she tested positive for a banned substance found in cold medicine.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Sports Editor:</p>
        <p>Rules are created so mayhem doesn't occur. There comes a time when a governing body has to take a step back and try to think outside the box. The International Olympic Committee needs to do this after stripping Andreea Raducan, the Romanian gymnast, of her gold medal in the all-around because she tested positive for a banned substance found in cold medicine.</p>
        <p>This young woman has sacrificed her childhood to realize her dream. Obviously there is a major difference in this case; she didn't use this stimulant to enhance her performance. She was sick. How can this be viewed in the same light as athletes who knowingly try to cheat with performance-enhancing drugs? The I.O.C. needs to give back her gold medal. She did not cheat. That's the only reason for drug testing -- to see if someone cheats.</p>
        <p>ERROL ARNE  New Fairfield, Conn.</p>
      </block>
